Revision history for EV-WebKit

0.03  2026-07-21
        - fingerprint: opt-in readback noise via a new seed => <int> option. Perturbs canvas and OffscreenCanvas (getImageData/toDataURL/toBlob/convertToBlob), AudioContext (AudioBuffer.getChannelData/copyFromChannel and the AnalyserNode float frequency + time-domain readers) and WebGL readPixels with a seeded, content-independent function keyed on absolute canvas/drawing-buffer coordinates (the frame index for audio), so the same sample re-read through any API, rectangle or offset gives the same value. An opaque pixel gets an LSB flip; a partially transparent one moves to an adjacent REACHABLE value, because getImageData un-premultiplies and only a lattice of values is producible at a given alpha. Only engine-rendered audio buffers are touched, never one the page authored. The hash is stable within a session, differs from the automation host's output (hides llvmpipe) and differs across seeds; the seed is reduced modulo 2**32. Without seed, readback is untouched.
        - fingerprint: the JS coherence layer was substantially reworked. matchMedia now evaluates compound, comma-separated, "only"/"not"-prefixed and range-syntax queries clause by clause (delegating unspoofed clauses to the engine) and answers device-width/device-height from the spoofed screen; previously only a few literal query strings matched and a desktop dpr-1 profile got no override at all, so a binary search over (device-width: Npx) recovered the real host geometry. navigator.userAgentData and screen.orientation are now real WebIDL interfaces (correct toStringTag, prototype attributes, interface objects) rather than object literals; screen.orientation is exposed on desktop profiles too; userAgentData.brands is frozen as real Chrome returns it; and all four ontouch* handlers are installed together rather than ontouchstart alone.
        - fingerprint: webgl_vendor for the two Safari presets changed from "Apple" to "Apple Inc.", the string WebKit actually reports. $b->fingerprint returns the new value.
        - fingerprint: WebGL now spoofs the full per-profile capability set -- the numeric getParameter pnames (MAX_TEXTURE_SIZE, MAX_VIEWPORT_DIMS, MAX_VERTEX_ATTRIBS, ...), getSupportedExtensions, getExtension and getShaderPrecisionFormat -- for both WebGL1 and WebGL2, matching the claimed GPU family (ANGLE/NVIDIA for windows-chrome, Apple/Metal for the Safari presets, Adreno for pixel-chrome) and coherent with the already-spoofed renderer string, instead of only the UNMASKED vendor/renderer strings. Vector parameters return the correct typed-array class per pname (Int32Array for MAX_VIEWPORT_DIMS, Float32Array for the ALIASED_*_RANGE pair). getExtension returns the real object when the host GL supports it, a minimal stub for an advertised-but-absent one (carrying that extension's constants for the commonly probed few, an empty object for the rest -- no stub has behaviour), and undef for anything not on the advertised list.
        - fingerprint: DOM feature-presence now matches the impersonated browser. A Chrome profile exposes navigator.connection/usb/bluetooth/getBattery/scheduling and RTCPeerConnection; the Android profile correctly omits hid/serial (desktop-only); a Safari profile exposes only storage + RTCPeerConnection. Each stub is installed ONLY when the build lacks the real API, so a WebKitGTK that ships one keeps it. Functional where feasible (connection.effectiveType, storage.estimate(), getBattery(), getDevices()); no real ICE or device access.
        - fingerprint: the injected config blob (window.__evwk_cfg) is now published once before the first reader and deleted after the last, so it leaves no window tell; previously the coherence layer deleted it before the WebGL layer could read it.
        - fingerprint: the RTCDataChannel stub carries per-instance state and its full member set. Its attributes were class constants shared by every channel, so createDataChannel('chat').label read back '' -- a break for page code and a one-expression inconsistency to probe -- and maxPacketLifeTime, maxRetransmits, protocol, negotiated, id, bufferedAmount, bufferedAmountLowThreshold and binaryType were absent entirely. The options bag is now honoured, binaryType is writable and rejects an out-of-enum value with a TypeError as Chrome does, send() on a channel that never opens throws InvalidStateError rather than silently doing nothing, and close() moves readyState to closing then closed and fires a close event.
        - fingerprint: an onX handler assigned to any stub interface is now actually invoked when that interface dispatches an event. The handler accessors stored the value but nothing called it, so an event reached an addEventListener listener and never the onX one -- an asymmetry no real EventTarget has. A trampoline listener is registered once on first assignment, which also preserves the real ordering rule that an EventHandler keeps the position it was FIRST set at.
        - fingerprint: screen.orientation.type now follows the spoofed screen's aspect instead of the mobile flag, which made a portrait desktop or landscape tablet profile contradict its own screen.width/height.
        - build: `make` now rebuilds the web-process extension when wext/evwk_fp.c changes. It was compiled only by `perl Makefile.PL`, so editing the C and running `make test` silently tested the previous binary -- found when a deliberate mutation failed to break the suite.
        - doc: the Ceiling POD now also records two residuals found while trying to close them. navigator.languages is not a FrozenArray (a real browser caches one frozen array; this returns a fresh mutable one): caching one per JS context works, but a JSCValue strongly references its JSCContext, so cache/array/context is a refcount cycle whose destroy notify never runs and a whole JS context leaks per navigation -- measured, not theorised -- while anchoring the array JS-side would make languages a data property where every browser has an accessor. And navigator.plugins is not spoofed at all, which is right for the desktop and iOS presets but likely wrong for Chrome on Android.
        - doc: the Ceiling POD is rewritten for the new state and its honest residuals -- toString-detectable wrappers, content-independent noise being undoable by a known-image probe (and readback being undisguised without seed), canonical-per-family WebGL caps, and non-functional stub extensions / RTCPeerConnection.
        - packaging: add the network-fingerprint tests (t/96-network-coherence.t, t/97-network-fingerprint.t, t/98-curl-target.t) to MANIFEST -- they were omitted in 0.02 and so did not ship in the dist.

0.02  2026-07-16
        - network_fingerprint => : also match the connection fingerprint (TLS JA3/JA4 + HTTP/2 Akamai) to the fingerprint => profile, so the origin sees one coherent device at the network layer too. Requires fingerprint. Spins an in-process Proxy::Impersonate on the instance's EV loop, terminates WebKit's TLS locally, and re-originates each request as the matching real browser via libcurl-impersonate. The curl target is derived from the profile (windows-chrome->chrome131, macos-safari->safari18_0, iphone-safari->safari18_0_ios, pixel-chrome->chrome131_android), overridable with a string. The profile's identity headers (User-Agent, Sec-CH-UA, and a Chrome-format Accept-Language derived from the profile languages -- WebKit's own is not forwarded, since libsoup may format it unlike Chrome) are forced over curl's target defaults, so a Windows profile stays Windows on the macOS-built chrome131 target (Windows/macOS Chrome share the same TLS). WebKit accepts the proxy cert via set_tls_errors_policy('ignore') (WebKitGTK exposes no custom-CA path -- spiked: it honors neither SSL_CERT_FILE nor a settable GTlsDatabase). Requires the optional Proxy::Impersonate toolchain; croaks if unavailable; mutually exclusive with proxy =>. Accessors network_fingerprint/proxy_port; the proxy is shut down on quit. Out of scope: WebSockets, HTTP/3.
        - network_fingerprint: also answer Sec-CH-UA-WoW64 (?0) and the deprecated singular Sec-CH-UA-Full-Version when a host Accept-CHes them, matching what the JS getHighEntropyValues() reports -- otherwise the JS and HTTP channels contradict for a Chrome profile.
        - fingerprint: correct the Chrome sec-ch-ua / navigator.userAgentData.brands ORDER to real Chrome 131's (Google Chrome, Chromium, Not_A Brand -- GREASE last). The presets had the GREASE brand first, which -- though the JS and HTTP layers agreed -- did not match the browser whose TLS/UA the stack impersonates.
        - fingerprint: pixel-chrome now ships Chrome 131's reduced/frozen Android UA ("Android 10; K") instead of the raw "Android 14; Pixel 8"; the real device and OS version ride only in Sec-CH-UA-Model / -Platform-Version + navigator.userAgentData, matching curl-impersonate's chrome131_android. No stock Chrome 131 emits the raw model in the UA string.
        - doc: the fingerprint ceiling now names DOM API-surface / feature-presence detection (e.g. 'RTCPeerConnection' in window, 'connection' in navigator) -- WebKitGTK exposes neither Blink's nor Apple Safari's exact interface set, so a presence probe can reveal the engine regardless of the spoofed values, like the existing canvas/audio/WebGL caveats.
        - fingerprint presets refreshed to current versions with exact curl-impersonate targets: windows-chrome/pixel-chrome -> Chrome 131, macos-safari/iphone-safari -> Safari 18.

0.01  2026-07-02
        - initial release: async WebKitGTK 6.0 browser automation on EV
        - fingerprint => : present as a coherent real device (navigator/screen/WebGL) via native [native code] getters installed by a bundled C web-process extension (compiled at install against glib/gobject; degrades gracefully -- see fingerprint_available). Presets windows-chrome/macos-safari/iphone-safari/pixel-chrome, overridable; construct-time only. navigator/screen getters are fully native (prototype-installed, enumerable, irreversible). A coherence layer adds, per profile: window.chrome + navigator.userAgentData (Chrome), and mobile window-sizing + ontouchstart + pointer/hover/resolution media overrides (mobile). The coherence layer and the WebGL getParameter override are JS (native-looking but Function.prototype.toString.call-detectable). JS-property + toString layer only -- canvas/audio/TLS untouched
        - user content: add_user_script/add_user_style inject caller JS/CSS (document start/end, main or isolated world, all/top frames, allow/deny URL globs); each returns a handle with ->remove; remove_all_user_scripts/remove_all_user_styles clear only the caller's items (never the module's own BOOT)
        - validation hardening: an undef entry in any URL-pattern/host list (add_user_script/style allow/deny, set_proxy ignore) marshalled to a NULL that silently truncated the list WebKit received (a deny-list/no-proxy bypass) -- now croaks; an empty allow/deny list (which WebKit reads as match-all) and a ref/undef source likewise croak; and new(), set_proxy, and set_cookie now reject unknown/typo'd option keys instead of silently falling back to a more permissive default (e.g. a mistyped proxy => routing direct, or a mistyped secure => dropping the cookie flag)
        - pdf() and the cookie operations (set_cookie/cookies/clear_cookies/save_cookies/load_cookies) now have an internal watchdog timeout (per-instance timeout=>, plus pdf(..., timeout=>SECONDS) per call): a stuck op resolves its callback with 'timeout' -- the same error every other timed op in the API uses -- instead of hanging forever. pdf()'s deadline runs from the call, so it also bounds the time spent queued behind other prints: a job still queued at its deadline is dropped unprinted, while one already printing keeps the view until the engine really finishes it (WebKit-6.0's PrintOperation has no cancel at all, and a second print started alongside a live one crashes the engine)
        - navigation API: back/forward/reload/stop/can_go_back/can_go_forward
        - chrome => 1: minimal browser chrome (header bar + address entry)
        - cookie_jar: native persistent storage (expiry preserved); save/load_cookies become explicit snapshot calls
        - fix: instances are collectable after quit() (weakened GI/signal closures)
        - html(): full-document markup accessor
        - fix: UTF-8 round-trip across the JS bridge; epoch-stamped element handles (stale detection across navigations)
        - fix: uniform early-error delivery (clean tick, $b return); post-quit go/load_html; mock_scheme latin-1 bodies
        - fix: overlapping-navigation callback cross-talk (generation/uri-gated resolution); wait_for propagates is_visible errors
        - fix: overlapping-navigation cross-talk also for back/forward/reload/load_html (started-gate)
        - fix: overlapping-navigation finished-path false-success (committed-uri + superseded-uri gating)
        - fix: pdf write-verification; set_proxy uri validation; type/clear support contenteditable + reject non-editable; settings/set_user_agent usage croaks
        - fix: find/find_all surface a clean error (not a silent hang) on a tampered/unexpected page result
        - security: element registry + find/find_all/html/wait_for/all element accessors now run in a dedicated isolated JavaScript world; a hostile page cannot see or overwrite window.__evwk, redirect an element handle, or corrupt result marshalling by redefining JSON.stringify / polluting Object.prototype (script/script_async stay in the page's main world by design)
        - fix: quit() now resolves EVERY in-flight async callback (script/find/find_all/html/screenshot/pdf/cookie ops) exactly once with 'browser closed' instead of silently dropping it -- previously only wait_for and navigation callbacks were flushed, so a caller awaiting an in-flight op at quit()-time could hang
        - fix: quit()/DESTROY while a cookie-manager op (cookies/set_cookie/save_cookies) was in flight could use-after-free the network session in WebKit and crash (segfault); the native objects are now kept alive across the op and released on a clean tick
        - fix: every async method now croaks synchronously on a non-coderef callback instead of hanging the caller's EV::run (the die used to be swallowed inside a completion closure)
        - fix: reload() on a browser that never navigated resolves immediately with 'nothing to reload' instead of stalling the full timeout; go(undef) and set_cookie(non-hashref) deliver clean errors instead of leaking raw exceptions
        - fix: a throwing on_dialog callback no longer wedges the WebView (and sibling instances) -- the exception is caught, the dialog resolved, and WebKit's native dialog still suppressed
        - fix: settings() rejects a reference value (was silently numified into a garbage integer) and validates all values before applying any; set_user_agent() (and the new(user_agent=>...) option) verify the UA actually applied and croak if WebKit silently rejected it (control chars, bytes >= 0x80, leading/trailing whitespace, embedded quote/backslash, ...)
        - fix: superseding a callback-less navigation (a normal navigate-away) no longer spuriously fires on_error -- only a genuine failure with no callback waiting does
        - fix: pdf() on a view that never loaded a page no longer segfaults deep in WebKit's C print path -- it delivers a clean 'pdf: no page loaded' error (a native crash no eval could catch)
        - fix: pdf() serializes its PrintOperations (one at a time per instance) -- concurrent pdf() calls used to race at the WebKit level (a failing op could report a false success or clobber a concurrent one); they are now queued and resolve deterministically
        - fix: a throw in pdf()'s PrintOperation setup (e.g. a $path or option whose stringification dies) now reaches the callback and frees the queue slot, instead of throwing synchronously out of pdf() and wedging the queue (starving every later pdf())
        - fix: an instance is now collected by a bare drop (undef/scope-exit), not only after an explicit quit() -- its native signal handlers, the mock_scheme uri-scheme handler, and the per-navigation timers all hold only weak references to it, so DESTROY (and the quit it runs) fires without leaking a window/view/session per dropped instance, even mid-navigation
        - fix: find()/find_all() with an omitted callback no longer die in the completion; a navigation failure with no per-call callback now reaches on_error; a throwing per-call navigation callback no longer skips on_load
        - fix: quit() is exception-safe. It runs your callbacks in order to resolve them, and the two flush loops invoked each one unguarded -- so the first die unwound quit() entirely: every callback queued behind it was silently dropped AND the teardown below the loops never ran, leaking the native window, the WebView (with its web+network processes), the context and the session for the life of the process. Nothing could retry (_dead is set on quit()'s first line, so a later quit()/DESTROY returns at once), and via a bare drop (DESTROY evals quit) it happened in complete silence. Each invocation is now guarded, the exception reported with warn, and the native teardown always completes
        - fix: quit() called from inside an event handler (on_dialog/on_policy/on_console, a mock_scheme producer) no longer wedges the event loop. Those handlers run inside WebKit's own GLib dispatch frame, and quit()'s flush delivered every OTHER in-flight callback nested in it -- callbacks the API promises arrive on a clean tick and documents as safe to EV::break from. An EV::break there busy-spins the next EV::run (the EV::Glib lifecycle wedge): the process hung outright. quit() now defers the whole teardown to a clean tick when it is called from a dispatch frame
        - fix: a navigation callback is no longer dropped when quit() lands in the ~30ms settle window (the nav had left {pending} but had not yet been delivered, so it was in no registry and nothing flushed it): a go() that succeeded and was quit() in that window never called back at all. It now resolves exactly once with 'browser closed', like every other in-flight op
        - fix: an instance dropped with a callback delivery still pending is collected at once. _defer/_defer_final were the only two closure sites in the module that captured $self strongly (self -> hash -> timer -> closure -> self) -- and every async completion and early-error guard funnels through them. The cycle self-healed one tick later, which is exactly why every collectability test missed it (they all spin a tick first). _defer_final's timer no longer hangs off the instance at all, so its callback still fires even if the browser is dropped first
        - fix: EV::WebKit::Element's 13 accessors (and its find/find_all) now croak synchronously on a non-coderef callback, as every browser-level method already did -- the die used to land inside the completion, where $EV::DIED swallows it and the caller's EV::run hangs forever
        - fix: a dying on_policy handler now BLOCKS the navigation (fail closed) and warns, instead of letting WebKit apply its own default -- allow. on_policy is a gate: a page able to provoke a die in the handler (a uri that breaks its parsing) walked straight through it. on_console is likewise guarded now
        - fix: pdf() no longer releases the queue slot if the throw came from print() itself -- it cannot be known whether the engine had already started, and a second PrintOperation alongside a live one crashes WebKit; the slot is held for finished/failed instead (callers stay bounded by their own watchdogs). The queue's continuation timer is now owned by quit() like every other timer
        - doc: set_cookie/cookies documented error strings now match what the code delivers ("set_cookie: missing '<key>'", 'cookies: uri required'); quit() resolves an in-flight navigation with 'browser closed' (was 'quit'), so a closed browser is ONE string across the whole API; pdf()'s resolution option is documented as inert (WebKitGTK's print-to-PDF path ignores it -- 72/300/1200 dpi produce byte-identical files); load_cookies does honour an expires key in a hand-written snapshot; the README SYNOPSIS quit()ed while an element's text() was still in flight and so always printed an empty heading
        - fix: quit() from inside a mock_scheme producer wedged the loop -- the producer runs in WebKit's dispatch frame like on_dialog/on_policy/on_console, but was the one handler never marked as such (while the POD promised it was covered)
        - fix: a bare DROP from inside any of those handlers wedged the loop too. DESTROY cannot defer its teardown (a strong ref to a refcount-0 object resurrects a corpse), so it tore down in place -- flushing callbacks nested in WebKit's frame. The natives are still released in place; only the CALLBACK delivery is deferred, which needs nothing from the instance
        - fix: on_error could fire ZERO times. It is the only notification a callback-less navigation failure ever gets, yet it belonged to no registry, so a quit() or drop landing in the one-tick delivery gap swallowed the failure silently
        - fix: on_dialog/on_policy/on_console could still invoke user code after quit() had completed (they never checked _dead)
        - fix: a mock_scheme producer that threw while serving a SUBRESOURCE (img/script/iframe) failed the top-level navigation whose page had in fact loaded fine -- or, if the nav had already resolved, was misreported through on_error. Only the navigation's own request resolves the navigation now
        - fix: wait_for(visible => 1) failed outright on a page that re-renders the node it is waiting for. It needs two round-trips (find, then is_visible), and a node replaced in between made the handle stale -- delivered as a terminal error rather than polled through. Staleness is transient there (each poll re-finds); real errors still propagate
        - fix: settings({user_agent => ...}) bypassed set_user_agent's validation entirely -- WebKit silently rejects a bad UA (keeps the old one, raises nothing), so it reported success while nothing had changed
        - fix: a second instance asking for a different display => was silently ignored (GTK connects to one display per process); it croaks now, instead of coming up on the wrong screen -- or "succeeding" on a display that does not exist
        - fix: an on_load handler that throws no longer discards the per-call navigation callback's own exception
        - test: the suite is now proven against mutation. The wedge was only ever tested through script(); every other op family is covered now (t/58), in a child process, so a wedge FAILS instead of hanging forever. save_cookies was the one op missing from the quit-flush battery, load_cookies the one missing from the non-coderef-callback sweep, and cookies/clear_cookies/screenshot/set_cookie had no test pinning the uniform 'timeout' string. The chrome widgets are now weak-checked as an island of their own (quit() cuts them loose from the browser, so every existing collectability test passed regardless)
        - fix: a navigation whose web process dies (crashed / out of memory / terminated) sat there for the WHOLE timeout and then reported a misleading 'timeout'. WebKit says so immediately (web-process-terminated), but sends no load-failed for the page that was loading, and the signal was never connected -- so the callback waited 30s by default for something that became impossible the instant the renderer died. It now resolves promptly with 'web process terminated: <reason>', and a crash with no navigation pending reaches on_error instead of being silent
        - fix: the element registry grew without bound. Every find() registered the node it matched -- and wait_for re-runs find() on every poll, 20 times a second by default -- so a page that never navigates (a long-lived single-page app: exactly what this module automates) accumulated one entry per call forever, each one pinning its DOM node in the renderer's JS heap. Nodes are deduplicated now, and detached ones swept out
        - fix: a mock_scheme producer that threw on the document of a reload()/back()/forward() was ignored, so the navigation reported a false SUCCESS while the page showed the error placeholder. (Those three have no predictable target uri, which the subresource check above had gated on; it uses the view's current uri instead)
        - fix: save_cookies names the URI whose fetch failed, instead of a bare error for a whole fan-out
        - test: mutation testing round 2 (44 mutants). Every previously-closed gap verified genuinely closed, and the survivors fixed: quit() from on_policy or on_console had NO wedge coverage at all (deleting their dispatch-frame marker left the whole suite green while the loop wedged) -- all four frames are covered now, in child processes so a wedge fails instead of hanging; on_error's stray-failure branch, the DESTROY-runs-exactly-once guarantee (two independent guards stop the teardown resurrecting a refcount-0 object, and removing either was invisible), the leftover-superseded-identity reset (a stale entry makes a LATER nav's own 'finished' look stray, hanging it to timeout), and the chrome widgets' own self-cycles (weak-checking only the chrome hash missed them: a widget held by its own handler leaks while the hash still collects)
        - test: t/56-pdf-queue.t was NOT green on a busy machine -- its fixed watchdogs doubled as the loop-exit under load, so EV::run returned before the prints finished and the assertions judged an unfinished run. Budgets scale off a measured print now, and a failsafe that fires says so instead of failing silently. The zero-timeout cookie/screenshot checks likewise retry rather than racing their own watchdog. The wedge tests run first (t/05), so a wedge regression fails cleanly before the in-process tests hang on it
        - on_close: the user closing the window (titlebar X, alt-F4, the window manager) is now handled. It never was: the instance just kept running with no window -- every in-flight callback dangled, the natives leaked, and the caller's EV::run went on spinning over nothing. Closing the window now resolves every in-flight callback with 'browser closed', destroys the window, and then calls on_close. Unlike on_dialog/on_policy/on_console, on_close is delivered on a clean EV tick, so EV::break is safe from it -- which is how a visible browser's EV::run returns: new(chrome => 1, on_close => sub { EV::break })
        - eg/browser.pl: a real, visible browser (address bar, back/forward/reload, devtools). MANIFEST was also stale -- every test file this release added was missing from it, so `make dist` was shipping an incomplete distribution
        - on_navigate: report navigation the API did not start. on_load fires only for a navigation this API began, so clicking a link in a visible window changed the page and told nobody at all -- the module could not observe the one thing an interactive browser most obviously does. on_navigate fires for every committed navigation, whoever caused it; on_load keeps its meaning, so an API navigation fires both
        - get/set accessors for every on_* handler, so code that did not construct the browser can observe it -- and can chain an existing handler rather than clobbering it. The console proxy installs on demand, so on_console works when set after construction (from the next navigation: user scripts are injected at document start)
        - EV::WebKit::Control + EV::WebKit::Client: drive an already-running instance from another process, over a unix socket (newline-delimited JSON). The window eg/browser.pl opens was a dead end -- you could watch it, but nothing could ask it anything. Now a script can attach to a long-lived browser (the greeting tells it where that browser already is), do its work, and leave it running with its cookies and logins intact; several clients can drive one browser at once. The client is blocking by default (say $c->title) and EV-native with ev => 1. The server is a pure consumer of the public API, so it can do nothing to the browser your own code could not. on_dialog/on_policy decisions stay LOCAL: answering them remotely would mean holding WebKit's dispatch frame open across a socket round-trip. The socket is the auth boundary -- 0600, no world-writable directory, no TCP -- because anyone who can open it can run arbitrary JavaScript in the browser and read every cookie it holds
        - eg/control.pl: attach to a running browser, drive it, leave it running
        - control protocol hardening (first adversarial review of Control/Client): fixed a batch of ways a client could hang or the browser could be taken down. wait_for over the wire hung forever (it resolves with an element, like find, which the JSON encoder cannot serialize -- and an unencodable result now becomes an error, never silence, for every method). screenshot(bytes=>1) wrote a file literally named "bytes" server-side and never base64'd the image. quit/close dropped a client's own quit-ack and the close event (buffered output is now drained before the socket closes). el.attr/prop/type over the wire hung on a short argument list (the appended callback landed in the name slot). A client SIGPIPE'd the process on any call after the browser was gone; a throwing ev-mode callback dropped its siblings; disconnect() abandoned in-flight callbacks; ->hello was never set in ev mode; a blocking call from inside on_event ate the outer call's answer. A poisoned decoder, a request pipelined after quit, and a client killed mid-request are all handled cleanly now
        - a lone UTF-16 surrogate anywhere in a page (an ordinary binary-to-string slip, some minifiers) no longer breaks html()/script()/element text -- the JS marshalling repairs it to U+FFFD, exactly as WebKit's own native title() does, instead of failing the whole read
        - fix: on_close fired more than once if the window got several close-requests before the deferred teardown ran (a double-click on the X, a window manager re-sending the delete); the native window was always destroyed once, but the notification doubled
        - fix: a self-referencing subresource (a page fetching its own uri, or the <img src=""> footgun) that failed no longer fails the navigation whose document already loaded -- only the first request for the document's uri is the document
        - data_dir => $path: persist and restore a full session (localStorage, IndexedDB, cache, and cookies), not just cookies. Everything is written under $path, isolated from other instances, and restored by a later instance with the same path. Cookies persist under the same rule as cookie_jar (those with an expiry), to a $path/cookies.sqlite; session cookies and sessionStorage are the two things WebKit never writes to disk. cache_dir overrides the derived $path/cache. Forces non-ephemeral like cookie_jar and composes with it (cookie_jar overrides the cookie file with its own queryable path). data_dir + ephemeral, and cache_dir without data_dir, croak
        - fix: the chrome address bar (and back/forward state, window title) now tracks a single-page-app navigation. A history.pushState -- how most modern sites change the URL on a click -- fires no load-changed cycle, and the chrome only refreshed on load-changed, so the bar showed a stale URL while the page had moved on. It now also refreshes on the view's notify::uri.
